All you need is a pair of shoes and a six-foot buffer from the next person.
(Some New York City paths, however, have gotten crowded with runners and walkers, making social distancing even there a challenge.)
Teenagers on bicycles are barking at their parents to catch up, like an elite coach prepping an Olympic hopeful.
There are runners in jeans and runners in expensive “athleisure” kits that look like they have never seen sweat.
There are families pulling each other with games of “first one to the light post wins” and friends running with an awkward amount of space between each other.